  "prompt": "What is the origin of Kapoor caste?",
  "response": "The Kapoor caste is traditionally associated with the Khatri community, which is a prominent caste within the Hindu social hierarchy in India, particularly in the Punjab region. The Khatri community has historically been involved in trade, commerce, and administrative roles.\n\nThe name \"Kapoor\" is derived from the Sanskrit word \"Karp\u016bra,\" which means \"camphor.\" Historically, the Kapoor surname is common among the Khatri caste, and many families with this surname can trace their lineage back to specific regions in Punjab.\n\nThe Kapoor family, which is well-known in the Indian film industry, has its roots in the Peshawar region (now in Pakistan) and belongs to the Khatri caste. They migrated to India during the Partition of India in 1947.\n\nIt's important to note that caste identities and histories can be complex and vary widely among different families and communities. The information provided here is a general overview and may not apply to every individual or family with the Kapoor surname.",
